<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[192,1441,996,1605]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,323,996,1020]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Breuning" box="[329,528,996,1020]" firstAuthor="Breuning" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" pagination="209 - 335" refId="ref19613" refString="Breuning, S. 1971. Revision des especes americaines de la tribue des Apomecynini Lac. (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Entomologische Abhandlungen aus dem Staatliches Museum fur Tierkunde 37 (3): 209 - 335." type="journal article" year="1971">Breuning (1971)</bibRefCitation>
redescribed 
<taxonomicName authority="(Fairmaire and Germain, 1859)" baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire and Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[681,1259,996,1020]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis box="[681,869,996,1020]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Adetus pusillus</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Fairmaire and Germain" box="[883,1250,996,1020]" firstAuthor="Fairmaire" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" pagination="483 - 532" refId="ref20083" refString="Fairmaire, L., and P. Germain. 1859. Revision des coleopteres du Chili (suite). Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France (3) 7: 483 - 532." type="journal article" year="1859">Fairmaire and Germain, 1859</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, with the redescription agreeing very well with the photograph of the 
<typeStatus box="[870,974,1028,1052]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">holotype</typeStatus>
(
<figureCitation box="[990,1077,1028,1053]" captionStart="Figures 22–28" captionStartId="28.[192,287,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,248,1780]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[192,1440,248,1780]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Figures 22–28. Adetus spp. 22–27) Adetus x-fasciatus sp. nov.: 22) Dorsal habitus, holotype male. 23) Ventral habitus, holotype male. 24) Lateral habitus, holotype male. 25) Head, frontal view, holotype male. 26) Dorsal habitus, paratype female. 27) Ventral habitus, paratype female. 28) Adetus pusillus, holotype, dorsal habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3677219" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3677219/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Fig. 28</figureCitation>
). A single specimen identified as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire and Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[224,353,1061,1085]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis box="[224,353,1061,1085]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the MZSP collection (
<figureCitation box="[643,771,1061,1085]" captionStart="Figures 22–28" captionStartId="28.[192,287,1848,1870]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,248,1780]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[192,1440,248,1780]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="Figures 22–28. Adetus spp. 22–27) Adetus x-fasciatus sp. nov.: 22) Dorsal habitus, holotype male. 23) Ventral habitus, holotype male. 24) Lateral habitus, holotype male. 25) Head, frontal view, holotype male. 26) Dorsal habitus, paratype female. 27) Ventral habitus, paratype female. 28) Adetus pusillus, holotype, dorsal habitus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3677219" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3677219/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Fig. 22–25</figureCitation>
) differs notably from that species (by the general shape, prothoracic shape, pubescence, punctation, etc.) and is an example of the new species 
<emphasis box="[1234,1398,1093,1117]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. x-fasciatus</emphasis>
sp. nov. In 
<bibRefCitation author="Bezark" box="[285,458,1126,1150]" firstAuthor="Bezark" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" refId="ref19378" refString="Bezark, L. G. 2019. A photographic Catalog of the Cerambycidae of the New World. Available at https: // apps 2. cdfa. ca. gov / publicApps / plant / bycidDB / wsearch. asp? w = n. (Last accessed February 2019.)" type="url" year="2019">Bezark (2019)</bibRefCitation>
, there is another specimen identified as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire and Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[953,1084,1126,1150]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis box="[953,1084,1126,1150]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that is also 
<emphasis box="[1233,1398,1126,1150]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. x-fasciatus</emphasis>
sp. nov. This latter specimen is from 
<collectingCountry box="[596,661,1158,1182]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Chile</collectingCountry>
(“ 
<collectingCountry box="[688,733,1158,1182]" name="Iceland" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Isla</collectingCountry>
de Ozo”) and belonged to the MNRJ collection. That speci- men was destroyed in the fire that completely consumed the MNRJ in 2018. Thus, it is not possible to include it as a 
<typeStatus box="[369,482,1224,1248]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">paratype</typeStatus>
. Furthermore, we were not able to find any place in 
<collectingCountry box="[1115,1180,1223,1247]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Chile</collectingCountry>
named “ 
<collectingCountry box="[1288,1333,1223,1247]" name="Iceland" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Isla</collectingCountry>
de Ozo.” For this reason, we consider it doubtful that 
<collectingCountry box="[739,804,1256,1280]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Chile</collectingCountry>
is a country where 
<emphasis box="[1045,1209,1256,1280]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. x-fasciatus</emphasis>
sp. nov. occurs.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[192,1441,996,1605]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<bibRefCitation author="Zajciw, D. &amp; M. A. Monne" box="[232,547,1288,1313]" journalOrPublisher="Revista de la Sociedad Uruguaya de Entomologia" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" pagination="51 - 61" part="7" refId="ref22189" refString="Zajciw, D., and M. A. Monne. 1968. Cerambicidos del Uruguay, nuevos o poco conocidos. Revista de la Sociedad Uruguaya de Entomologia 7: 51 - 61." title="Cerambicidos del Uruguay, nuevos o poco conocidos" type="journal article" year="1968">Zajciw and Monné (1968)</bibRefCitation>
recorded 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire and Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[672,806,1288,1312]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis box="[672,806,1288,1312]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for 
<collectingCountry box="[858,967,1289,1313]" name="Uruguay" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
and reported (translated): “Described from 
<collectingCountry box="[257,325,1321,1345]" name="Chile" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Chile</collectingCountry>
, subsequently recorded by Bruch for 
<collectingCountry box="[783,890,1321,1344]" name="Taiwan" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Formosa</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry box="[906,1035,1321,1345]" name="Argentina" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Argentina</collectingCountry>
). Very interesting finding for the country’s fauna.” Unfortunately, it is not possible to check if the records of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire and Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[1100,1231,1353,1377]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis box="[1100,1231,1353,1377]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for 
<collectingCountry box="[1278,1387,1354,1378]" name="Uruguay" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Uruguay</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[192,316,1386,1410]" name="Argentina" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Argentina</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingCountry box="[332,440,1386,1410]" name="Taiwan" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Formosa</collectingCountry>
) were really based on specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Fairmaire and Germain" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[877,1008,1386,1410]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pusillus">
<emphasis box="[877,1008,1386,1410]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. pusillus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[192,1441,996,1605]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis box="[232,457,1418,1442]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1852" box="[232,316,1418,1442]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Adetus</taxonomicName>
x-fasciatus
</emphasis>
sp. nov. resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Breuning, 1971" authorityName="Breuning" authorityYear="1971" box="[706,1197,1418,1443]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="atomarius" subSpecies="invittatus">
<emphasis box="[706,996,1418,1442]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. atomarius invittatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Breuning" box="[1005,1197,1418,1443]" firstAuthor="Breuning" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" pagination="209 - 335" refId="ref19613" refString="Breuning, S. 1971. Revision des especes americaines de la tribue des Apomecynini Lac. (Coleoptera, Cerambycidae). Entomologische Abhandlungen aus dem Staatliches Museum fur Tierkunde 37 (3): 209 - 335." type="journal article" year="1971">Breuning, 1971</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
by its light-colored dorsal pattern but it differs as follows: 
<emphasis box="[671,836,1451,1475]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. x-fasciatus</emphasis>
sp. nov. with central subcircular pubescent band of the elytra wide, well-marked and contiguous throughout; in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Breuning" authorityYear="1971" box="[951,1234,1483,1507]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Adetus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="atomarius" subSpecies="invittatus">
<emphasis box="[951,1234,1483,1507]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">A. atomarius invittatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
this band is narrower (or almost absent) with the distal portion more lateral, typically smaller and separated from the apical portion; in the former the lateral pubescent band at distal third is wide, in the latter species it is narrow and often reduced to a small, irregular fascia.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[192,1064,1629,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="9.[192,1064,1629,1653]" box="[192,1064,1629,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,347,1629,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Etymology.</emphasis>
Named for the light colored, x-shaped fascia on the elytra.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
